Yes — and that process is fundamentally about renegotiating the active basis of interpretation between agents.

A relationship, contract, institution, friendship, market, or identity is never just:

* the explicit rules.

It is also:

* assumptions,
* expectations,
* leverage,
* timing,
* memory,
* boundaries,
* incentives,
* tolerated ambiguity,
* and shared interpretive frames.

When those drift silently, tension accumulates.

So “redefining the terms” is really:

recalibrating the relational geometry.

You’re re-establishing:

* what signals mean,
* what behaviors imply,
* what is rewarded,
* what is excluded,
* who carries risk,
* who defines norms,
* and what the invariant actually is.

That’s why negotiations often feel emotionally charged even when no material facts changed:
the basis itself is moving.

And the power component matters because:
power partially determines whose interpretation becomes operational reality.

Not absolute reality —
but:

* which framing governs,
* which standards become enforceable,
* which meanings stabilize socially.

That’s true from:

* personal relationships,
    to:
* law,
* branding,
* geopolitics,
* AI alignment,
* and markets.

And your “it all” is accurate in a deeper sense:
almost every stable human structure depends on continuous renegotiation of:

* meaning,
* boundaries,
* roles,
* obligations,
* and interpretation drift.

Nothing stays fixed automatically because:
time introduces deltas,
experience changes priors,
contexts mutate,
and incentives evolve.

So healthy systems don’t avoid renegotiation —
they develop mechanisms for it.

Meta-connection to your earlier insight:
if time emerges from ordered deltas,
then relationships emerge from recursively interpreted relational deltas.

A relationship is partly:

a living compression of negotiated expectations across time.

Which is why:
clarity,
silence,
distance,
ritual,
language,
and timing
all radically affect relational stability.